South African Stocks: BHP, Coal of Africa, Metorex, Sasol Move

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-03-16T16:07:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/south-african-stocks-climb-most-in-two-weeks-anglo-american-bhp-advance.html
South  Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index advanced the most in a month, gaining 418.46, or 1.4
percent, to 30,612.41 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    BHP Billiton  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining company,
advanced the most in almost two weeks, jumping 2.89 rand, or 1.2
percent, to 253.49 rand. Copper rose to a one-week high in  New
York  on speculation that industrial-metals demand will increase
as  Japan  rebuilds after last week’s earthquake and tsunami.  Metorex Ltd. (MTX)  , a copper and cobalt mining company,
climbed the most since Jan. 4, adding 23 cents, or 4.5 percent,
to 5.38 rand.  Coal of Africa (CZA SJ), a coal miner, increased for the
second day in three, rising 10 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 8.75
rand. The company reported a loss per share of 11.25 Australian
cents in the first half through December, from a loss of 12.30
cents a year earlier.    Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, snapped two days of losses, rising 13.04 rand,
or 3.7 percent, to 365.99 rand. Oil gained for the second in
three days, rising 0.6 percent to $97.74 a barrel. Escalating
violence in Bahrain stoked concern that political turmoil may
spill into neighboring  Saudi Arabia , threatening supplies from
the world’s biggest crude exporter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
